<h1>@HI{{yo}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @FORMATION{{@S{{}} @HI{{@EM{{yo}}}}.}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{yo}}}} is a sentence ending particle.
</p>

@BGRNDSTART{{}}

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{yo}}}} can urge a course of action.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ano@KJ{{unfold^perusal^meeting}}he@KJ{{going}}ttemimashou@EM{{ne}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Come on, lets' go to that exhibition.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{yo}}}} can indicate a request (in this usage it is stronger than <a href="grammar-particle-ne.html">@HI{{ne}}</a>).

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}no@KJ{{house}}nimo@KJ{{come}}tekudasai@EM{{yo}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Come to <em>my</em> house too.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
<a name="assertion">@HI{{@EM{{yo}}}}</a> can indicate that the speaker feels certain of what he is saying.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{now^day}}ha@KJ{{gold^weekday^day}}desu@EM{{yo}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Today is Friday, you know?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRND{{}}
<p>
@HI{{@EM{{yo}}}} can indicate scolding or contempt.

<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ano@KJ{{person}}ha@KJ{{attend^matter}}ha dekinaiwa@EM{{yo}}.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      He just can't do the work!
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

@BGRNDEND{{}}

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
@HI{{@EM{{yo}}}} generally indicates that the speaker is convinced of something. It can be an assertion by the speaker
of something that he assumes is not known to the listener.
</p>

